T1  - PREFERENTIAL TRADE AGREEMENTS AND MULTILATERAL TARIFF COOPERATION*
AU  - Saggi, Kamal
Y1  - 2006/02/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2006.00371.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 29
EP  - 57
VL  - 47
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2006.00371.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Are preferential trade agreements (PTAs) building or stumbling blocks for multilateral trade liberalization? I address this question in an infinitely repeated tariff game between three countries engaged in intraindustry trade under oligopoly. The central result is that when countries are symmetric, a free trade agreement (FTA) undermines multilateral tariff cooperation by adversely affecting the cooperation incentive of the nonmember whereas a customs union (CU) does so via its effect on the cooperation incentives of members. However, when countries are asymmetric with respect to either market size or cost, there exist circumstances where PTAs facilitate multilateral tariff cooperation.
ER  - 

